For logistic regression analysis I chose sex, age, romantic and absences My hypoteses is that young single men with a lot of absences have high probability to high use of alcohol This hypoteses is build on real life experience, not scientific articles :)

# find the model with glm()
m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + age + romantic + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# print out a summary of the model
summary(m)

Based on logistic regression analysis, the hypoteses seems to be partially correct.

Men seems to have much higher probability of belonging to heavy users than women. Their Odds Ratio is 2.7. However, the confidence interval is wide (1.7-4.4) which means that the probability can be much smaller or higher. The result is also statistically significant.

Romantic relationship seems to lower the probability of high use as in hypoteses. Odds ratio is 0.74 when in a relationship. However, its not statistically significant, so we cant make these conclusions.

Age and absences dont have large impact on probabality of high use. Absences are statistically significant, age is not. Therefore, we can conclude that high number of absences slightly increase the probability of belonging to high users.

The last thing is to check the accuracy of predictions

# fit the model
m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   263    7
##    TRUE     89   23
# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2513089

The average number of wrong predictions is quite low

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Plot shows that predictor variable rad has a large impact on the model.
